WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.000
Hi everyone, my name is Isabelle Velazquez. Today we're going to be talking about how to create a Quarto dashboard with Python code.

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Quarto is an open source scientific and technical publishing system.

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:19.000
It allows you to create a variety of documents, such as reports, websites, and presentations, using code and text.

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:24.000
And as of Quarto 1.5, you can also create dashboards.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:33.000
Quarto dashboards are an easy way of creating interactive displays of data, text, tables, and plots that you can share with others.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:39.000
The data that we're going to be looking at today is water and security data from 2023.

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:42.000
This is data from the TidyTuesday project.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:55.000
TidyTuesday is a weekly project where datasets are released and everyone in the data science community is invited to play around with it, visualize it, and create something engaging or inspiring.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:05.000
So I will be using Positron as my IDE, but most of this experience will be somewhat similar if you use VS Code or another editor.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:11.000
One difference is that Quarto comes bundled with Positron, so we do not have to install it separately.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:18.000
But if you haven't configured Quarto in your editor, we have some resources to get started in the description.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:23.000
Assuming you have Quarto installed, we can proceed with creating our dashboard.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:35.000
In Positron, I hit Command-Shift-P to open up the command palette, then type Quarto new document, or navigate to it, to create a new Quarto document in a QMD file.

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:39.000
This is the file in which we will create our dashboard.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:47.000
I'm going to title my document Water and Security in the United States Western States 2023.

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:52.000
I'm going to paste each section of the document and walk through what each step is doing.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:56.000
In a Quarto document, we have what are called code chunks.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:02.000
They are denoted by three backticks and then the programming language that you want to use in curly braces.

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:07.000
In this case, Python is in the curly braces because we're going to be running Python.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:11.000
Quarto documents also allow you to include code chunk options.

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:16.000
These are instructions for how you would like to customize your code chunks in your render document.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:20.000
Include false is an example of a code chunk option.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:25.000
I want this code chunk to run, but not to show up in my render document.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:28.000
Within the script, you can put executable code.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:37.000
I have the script.py file that has all the document setup, such as importing the modules, reading the data, and cleaning it up.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:42.000
Rather than have everything within my QMD file and making it super long,

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:46.000
I have it split out so all the data cleaning steps are in the script,

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:51.000
and then the QMD file can solely include what I need for my dashboard.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:53.000
You do not have to do it this way.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:59.000
For example, you could instead read your CSV and clean it up in a code chunk in the QMD file.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:02.000
This is just how I decided to set up my project.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:05.000
Again, it's completely up to you.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:12.000
To actually execute the code, you can click run cell here, and everything within the code chunk will be run.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:20.000
In Positron, I can also preview my data, look at some histograms to see its distributions very quickly,

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:27.000
or just take a look at what are contained within the cells.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:32.000
Now I add another code chunk with more executable code.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:36.000
So I have this object called wi-west-2023-gt.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:42.000
I'm using the great tables package, create a table, call that object at the end of the code chunk,

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:51.000
and if I click run cell here, then I can see a preview of what this table will look like in Positron's viewer pane.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:59.000
This table shows the counties facing the most water insecurity and the percent lacking plumbing in that county.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:03.000
I'm going to include this table in my dashboard.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:05.000
Next, I'm going to create another code chunk.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:11.000
This one creates a box plot using that water insecurity data for the western states in 2023.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:19.000
I click run cell, and I can see a preview of what the plot will look like in Positron's plot viewer.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:24.000
In addition to viewing the plot directly in my IDE, I could also do things like save it,

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:30.000
copy the plot to the clipboard, and zoom in if I really wanted to look at it closely.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:34.000
But let's say I'm good with this plot, so we can continue with our dashboard.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:42.000
So just to recap, I have a code chunk that's reading my data, cleaning it up in a separate script.py file.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:47.000
Next, I have two code chunks for a table and a box plot using that data.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:49.000
So great!

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:57.000
If I scroll up here, I have format HTML, which is one of the formats that you can create with Porto.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:03.000
If I render this, it's going to produce an HTML page that I could, say, put in a website.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:12.000
If I want to see what my document looks like right now, first I save the document, call it index.qmd.

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:16.000
Then I can click this preview button up here.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:24.000
Notice in the terminal, it's executing each of the cells, and then in the viewer, I can see the rendered HTML document.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:29.000
Let's say I want to see what this looks like in the browser.

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:31.000
I can pop it out and take a look.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:36.000
I have the title up here, the first code chunk with the GT table,

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:42.000
and it's showing both the code and the output because I haven't specified any code chunk options in the document,

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:45.000
saying that I don't want to see the code.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:49.000
And then similarly, the second code chunk for the plot as well.

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:54.000
We're well on our way, but now let's say I would like to convert this to a dashboard.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:06:00.000
I return to my QMD file and specify format dashboard instead of format HTML.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:06.000
And that's it. This will change my Porto output from HTML to a dashboard.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:08.000
I can hit preview again.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:13.000
And the great thing about Porto is all of these different file types are native.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:21.000
Whether you're creating an HTML file, dashboard, presentation, you don't have to install anything separately.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:24.000
Everything is bundled within Porto itself.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:30.000
I pop out the rendered dashboard and I can see its first iteration.

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:35.000
By default, Porto dashboards are laid out first by row and by column.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:42.000
So each separate component, whether it be text or table or plots, will be put in a cell within the dashboard.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:47.000
So here I have my title and then my two code chunks as separate components,

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:51.000
one being the great tables table and the other being the box plot.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:54.000
Notice that the code isn't showing up in the dashboard.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:07:00.000
That's because the dashboard format assumes you don't want to show code and just want to display the output.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:03.000
But this dashboard is a little hard to read.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:10.000
Say instead I want for a single row to contain both the table and the plot.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:15.000
So I can go back and start configuring the layout using this idea of either rows or columns.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:20.000
I want the table to be its own column and I want the plot to be its own column in a single row.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:23.000
I can configure the layout using headings.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:27.000
Different levels of headings will define the layout of the dashboard.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:30.000
So here I'm saying in this row I want two separate columns.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:36.000
Since it's columns within the same row, I don't need to explicitly define them,

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:39.000
but I'll show you what that looks like in a bit.

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:45.000
The Corda dashboard will know that these should be in a single row because they're under the same heading.

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:52.000
I have my dashboard with a row with two columns, one of the columns being the table and the other being the plot.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:56.000
Here I can keep configuring the dashboard to look exactly the way I want.

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:01.000
So say this table, I want it to take up a little less space than 50%.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:05.000
Here I'm going to explicitly put the table in its own column.

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:10.000
And then in curly braces, I can say this column should take up 30% of the space.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:17.000
Then again, explicitly listing out the other column, say that this one should take up 70%.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:21.000
I can save and then hit preview.

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:25.000
When I pop it out, I can see this one here is a bit more narrow.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:28.000
This one's a bit wider.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:32.000
Corda also has extensive theming capabilities.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:36.000
There are over 20 built-in bootstrap themes that you could add.

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:40.000
So for example, I go back to my QMD file.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:46.000
Then I specify format, dashboard, theme, and I'm going to pick sandstone.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:51.000
Hit preview again, and now the sandstone theme has been applied.

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:58.000
You can also customize Corda dashboards with your custom theme or use the new brand.yaml capability.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:02.000
Brand.yaml allows you to customize Corda using a YAML file.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:12.000
And it's easy to put the same YAML file in different projects if you have something that you would like to say adhere to a corporate style guide or something like that.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:18.000
So this was a very brief overview of how to create Corda dashboards with Python.

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:23.000
Here I can publish to PositConnect Cloud so I can share with my organization and colleagues.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:27.000
And with that, please let us know what you would like to see next.

